    <div class="w-full lg:w-7/12 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mb-10">
        <h2 class="mb-4 font-serif text-3xl font-bold text-center uppercase sm:text-left sm:text-4xl text-oak">
          Common Tactics
        </h2>
        <hr class="w-4/5 mx-auto border-2 sm:w-full lg:w-4/5 border-oak sm:mx-0">
      </div>
      <div class="mb-8 text-lg text-center sm:text-left tactic-info-container">
        <div class="space-y-4 active-tactic-text" data-tactic="backrankMate">
          <p>
            <span class="font-bold">Back-rank mates</span> involve the rook (or queen) delivering checkmate along the
            back rank, often with the enemy king trapped behind its own pawns.
          </p>
          <p>
            This tactic exploits the fact that the rook can control an entire rank, and it is particularly effective
            when the opponent's king has limited mobility due to its own pieces blocking escape routes.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4" data-tactic="pins">
          <p>
            A <span class="font-bold">pin</span> is a tactical motif where a piece is immobilized because moving it
            would expose a more valuable piece behind it.
          </p>
          <p>
            This tactic is particularly effective against pieces that are pinned to the king, as any attempt to move
            the pinned piece would expose the king to check.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4" data-tactic="skewers">
          <p>
            A <span class="font-bold">skewer</span>, similar to a pin, is a tactic where a more valuable piece is in
            front of an undefended, less valuable piece.
          </p>
          <p>
            The more valuable piece is forced to move to avoid being captured, rendering the piece behind it vulnerable
            ready for capture on the next move.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4" data-tactic="forks">
          <p>
            A <span class="font-bold">fork</span> is a tactic which involves attacking two undefended or higher valued
            pieces at the same time, forcing the opponent to make a tough decision.
          </p>
          <p>
            The opponent can only save one of the pieces, at the expense of the other. On the next move, whichever piece
            was left undefended will be captured.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4" data-tactic="batteries">
          <p>
            A <span class="font-bold">battery</span> is a formation of heavy pieces which line up on the same file or
            rank, providing a powerful attacking force.
          </p>
          <p>
            This formation allows for coordinated attacks and can create multiple threats at once, making it difficult
            for the opponent to defend their position effectively.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
